1. Introduction¶

- 1.1 Data Description¶

The dataset comprises 10866 movies across 21 columns, the first 2 columns are basically IDs for the movies and the remaining 19 are typical variables descriping each entry. Worth mentioning that the data encompasses 56 years form 1960 to 2015.

df.shape
df.info()
df.release_year.nunique()
df.release_year.value_counts()

- 1.2 Problem Statemen¶

Given such information-rich dataset, some of the question that deserve answering are:

  1. Top ten movies in terms of (revenues, budget, Average votes, popularity).
  2. What are the geners of movies generating the highest revenue?
  3. What are the geners of movies consuming the highest budgets?
  4. What are geners of movies recieving the highest vote score?
  5. Film aficionados might have different interests. How have the general taste and preferences changed over years?
  6. Given that major films costing over 100 million to produce can still flop, this question is more important than ever to the industry.

From running the previous few line of codes the following issues are noticed:

  • There's only one duplicated row.
  • The column "homepage" has most of its values as null.
  • The budget and revenue columns are adjusted later with the budget_adj and revenue_adj columns.
  • The genres' entries pose a structural challenge to perform analyses on the individual genre level as there're many incidents of multiple genres per movie; the same applies for the cast and director columns.
  • The tagline and overview columns are not relevant to the insights we aim at gleaning.
  • Around 50% of the movies have 0 budgets and 0 revenues that have to be dealt with when analysing financial information.

Financial insights¶

As alluded in the introduction, we have almost half of the movies with zero budgets and zero revenues that might be a problem with the data collection or entry. So in counting for the financial figures, it is prudent to limit our analysis to the entries with positive budgets or revenues.

In [30]:
# Detrmining the non_zero movies for budgets and revenues 
non_zero_movies = pd.DataFrame(df.query('revenue_adj > 0 and budget_adj > 0'))
non_zero_movies['profit_loss'] = non_zero_movies['revenue_adj'] - non_zero_movies['budget_adj']

# Total count of non_zero_budget movies
non_zero_movies.shape[0]

non_zero_movies.query('profit_loss < 0')['original_title'].count() / non_zero_movies.shape[0]
Out[32]:
0.27815256875973016

So there is 3854 movies with positive budgets and revenues, 1072 of them recording loss which accounts for nearly 28% of the total movies.

Conclusions¶

In summary, the following insights can be gleaned and worth testing for verification in the other reports:

  1. There's no apparant correlation between the budget of a movie and its realized revenues, as well as its popularity and vote average seem not to be impacted by these factors.

  2. The genres of Drama, Action, adventure, Comedy and thriller are the highest in terms of revenue generating, invested budget and growing popularity over the time spane of the dataset.

  3. From the financial figures, the percentage of over-100-million-budget movies that flop (14%) are around half the percentage of the flopping movies' figure (28%), yet there's no gurantee that a hight budget movie can be a success.

In Addition , The dataset had the following limitations:

  1. Some of the variables included a great deal of null data that may result into misleading insights when analysed; such as the homepage column that i opted to delete.

  2. The zero budget and zero revenues values of almost 65% of the movies included in the dataset poses additional challenges when analysing the financial performance of the movies as a measure for success.

  3. The combined genres' records, director records, cast records requires special treatment to analyse them individually.
